You've already built this — and it's genuinely good. This is a Euterpea-inspired music algebra, and you've nailed the central insight. Let me talk about what makes this design work and the one place I think it could go deeper.

## What's right

The **sealed `Music` hierarchy with `+` (sequential) and `|` (parallel)** is the load-bearing design decision. Everything else flows from it. This is the same algebraic structure as process calculi (CCS, CSP) — two composition operators over an expression tree — and it's the right one because music literally *is* concurrent sequential processes. A fugue is message-passing between voices.

The decision to **separate `ChordSymbol` (harmonic identity) from `Chord` (voiced pitches)** is the kind of thing that looks obvious in retrospect but most music libraries get wrong. Lead sheets have chord symbols; scores have voiced chords; they're different types because they answer different questions. "What chord is this?" vs "What notes should I play?"

**Rational `Duration`** is correct and non-negotiable. Floating-point duration arithmetic means your measures don't add up, your tuplets drift, and you can't reliably compare rhythmic values for equality. You got this right.

**`RhythmPattern` as a separate concept** that gets "realized" with pitches captures something real: a clave pattern exists independent of any melody. You can apply the same tresillo to different pitch material. Rhythm and pitch are orthogonal axes that get multiplied together, not a single thing.

## Where it could go deeper: Form

The one structural concept missing is **repetition-with-variation** — the thing that distinguishes music from sound. Right now `repeat(3)` produces `a + a + a`, which is the *mechanics* of repetition but not the *semantics*. Music doesn't just repeat — it develops: ABA, AABA, theme-and-variations, sonata form, 12-bar blues.

The trade-off is between keeping `Music` minimal (a clean algebra) vs. encoding structural intent (which matters for analysis and generation). I'd keep `Music` clean and add a `Form` layer:

```dart
/// Form — the large-scale structure of musical discourse.
///
/// Form captures repetition-with-variation: the difference between
/// "play this twice" and "play this, then play a contrasting section,
/// then return to the first idea." The return carries meaning that
/// mechanical repetition doesn't.
sealed class Form {
  const Form();
}

/// A named section with its musical content.
final class Section extends Form {
  final String label;  // "A", "B", "Bridge", "Coda"
  final Music music;
  const Section(this.label, this.music);
}

/// Repeat a section with optional variation on each pass.
final class Repeated extends Form {
  final Section section;
  final int times;
  /// Transform applied on each successive repetition.
  /// Pass 0 = original, pass 1 = variation(original), etc.
  final Music Function(Music, int pass)? variation;
  const Repeated(this.section, this.times, {this.variation});
}

/// A sequence of formal sections: verse-chorus-verse, ABA, etc.
final class Structure extends Form {
  final List<Form> sections;
  const Structure(this.sections);

  /// Flatten to concrete Music by applying all variations.
  Music realize() { /* ... */ }
}
```

This lets you say things like "AABA form where each A transposes up a step" or "theme and five variations where each variation doubles the tempo" — which is how musicians actually think about large-scale structure.

The existing `Music` algebra stays untouched. `Form` is a layer *above* it that references sections by identity rather than duplicating their content. That's the key distinction: `repeat(3)` copies the tree three times; `Repeated(sectionA, 3)` says "this is the same idea, heard three times" — which matters if you later want to ask "what's the form of this piece?"

The rest of the system — pitch spelling with accidentals, enharmonic awareness, interval inversion, the modifier stack for dynamics and tempo — is solid. I wouldn't change it.

The mutex isn't protecting anything because each operation creates its own. Two concurrent operations each acquire *their own* mutex, both read the same value, both pass the condition check, and both write — hence the duplicates.

**The fix:** The mutex must be shared across all operations that touch the same resource. Keyed by whatever identifier represents the thing being guarded (a row ID, a user ID, etc.).

```
// BROKEN: each call gets its own lock
Future<void> updateWidget(String id) async {
  final mutex = Mutex();        // ← new lock every time
  await mutex.acquire();
  final widget = await db.read(id);
  if (widget.canUpdate) {
    await db.write(id, widget.updated());
  }
  mutex.release();
}

// FIXED: locks are shared per resource
final _locks = <String, Mutex>{};

Future<void> updateWidget(String id) async {
  final mutex = _locks.putIfAbsent(id, Mutex.new);
  await mutex.acquire();
  try {
    final widget = await db.read(id);
    if (widget.canUpdate) {
      await db.write(id, widget.updated());
    }
  } finally {
    mutex.release();
  }
}
```

If you're running **multiple server instances**, even a shared in-process mutex won't help — two processes each hold their own map. In that case, push the mutual exclusion into the database itself with either a `SELECT ... FOR UPDATE` (pessimistic row lock) or an optimistic concurrency check (`UPDATE ... WHERE version = @expectedVersion`, then retry on zero rows affected). The optimistic approach scales better because it avoids holding database locks during application logic, at the cost of retries under contention.
